{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1770995271,"nonce":"+Ss3HDpNB9EBUaloCHFLTtQIISs=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87qs4wt","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/200","origin":"github"},"title":"worktree_create.sh should track existing remote branch when available","message":"## Problem\n\nWhen `worktree_create.sh` is used with an issue number whose branch (`feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e`) already exists on the remote, it creates a new local branch from the current HEAD (typically `main`) instead of tracking the existing remote branch.\n\nThis means picking up work on an existing PR requires manual fixup:\n\n```bash\ngit fetch origin feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e\ngit reset --hard origin/feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e\ngit branch --set-upstream-to=origin/feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e\n```\n\n## Expected behavior\n\n`worktree_create.sh` should detect that `origin/feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e` exists and create the worktree tracking that remote branch, so the agent lands on the PR's current state without manual intervention.\n\n## Suggested approach\n\nBefore creating a new branch from HEAD, check if the branch exists on the remote:\n\n1. `git fetch origin` (or `git ls-remote --heads origin \"feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e\"`)\n2. If a matching remote branch exists, use `git worktree add \u003cpath\u003e --track -b feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e origin/feature/issue-\u003cN\u003e` (or equivalent)\n3. If no remote branch exists, keep the current behavior (branch from HEAD)\n\nThis would support the common multi-agent workflow where one agent opens a PR and another agent (or the same agent in a new session) needs to continue the work.\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}